
## 🧭 Phase 1: Foundations (QA mindset + basics)

This is where you learn *how QA thinks*.

You should understand:

* What QA actually does (not just “find bugs” — it’s about preventing them)
* Software Development Life Cycle (SDLC)
* Testing types:

  * Manual testing
  * Functional vs non-functional testing
  * Smoke, regression, sanity testing

Core skills:

* Writing clear bug reports (steps, expected vs actual, severity)
* Basic test case writing
* Understanding requirements (this is HUGE in real jobs)

👉 Goal: You can manually test an app and document issues like a professional.


---------------------------------------------------------------


## 🧪 Phase 2: Manual Testing Practice (real-world simulation)

Now you practice like you’re already in a QA team.

Learn:

* Test case design techniques:
  * Boundary Value Analysis
  * Equivalence Partitioning
  
* Test planning basics
* Exploratory testing (just “breaking” the app smartly)

Tools you can start using:

* Excel / Google Sheets (for test cases)
* Jira (or any bug tracker conceptually)
* Any demo app (login systems, ecommerce sites)

👉 Goal: You can fully test a feature and produce structured test documentation.


---------------------------------------------------------------


## 💻 Phase 3: Basic Technical Skills (this is where you level up)

Most QA jobs now expect some coding.

Start with:

* One programming language (Java OR Python recommended)
* Basic OOP concepts
* Writing simple test scripts

Then move into:

* Automation basics
* Understanding locators (CSS selectors, XPath)

👉 Goal: You can write simple automated tests and understand code structure.


---------------------------------------------------------------


## ⚙️ Phase 4: Automation Testing (core QA engineer skill)

This is where you become “industry-ready.”

Learn:

* Selenium (web automation)
* Test frameworks:

  * JUnit / TestNG (Java)
  * PyTest (Python)
* Test design for automation (not everything should be automated)

Also:

* Page Object Model (POM)
* Data-driven testing

👉 Goal: You can automate real user flows like login, checkout, forms, etc.


---------------------------------------------------------------


## 🔌 Phase 5: API Testing (very important in real companies)

Modern systems are API-heavy.

Learn:

* REST APIs basics (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
* Postman
* JSON structure
* Status codes (200, 404, 500, etc.)

Then:

* Automate API tests (RestAssured / Python requests)

👉 Goal: You can test backend systems without UI.


---------------------------------------------------------------


## 🧠 Phase 6: Advanced QA (what makes you stand out)

This is where you go from “tester” → “engineer”.

Learn:

* CI/CD basics (Jenkins, GitHub Actions)
* Git (version control)
* Performance testing basics (JMeter)
* Security testing basics (OWASP awareness)

Also:

* Agile / Scrum workflow (standups, sprints, tickets)

👉 Goal: You can work inside real dev teams smoothly.


---------------------------------------------------------------


## 🚀 Phase 7: Job-ready portfolio

Before applying, build proof of skill:

* GitHub projects:

  * Automated login tests
  * API test suite
  * Small framework (even simple is fine)
* Sample test cases (Excel or docs)
* Bug reports (screenshots + structured format)



---------------------------------------------------------------


## 🧩 Bonus: What companies REALLY want

Not just tools — they care about:

* Can you think like a user?
* Can you break things logically?
* Can you explain bugs clearly?
* Can you work with developers without drama?


---------------------------------------------------------------


## 🪜 Simple timeline (if you want structure)

* Month 1–2: Manual testing + SDLC
* Month 3–4: Basic coding + test design
* Month 5–7: Automation (Selenium + framework basics)
* Month 8+: API + CI/CD + portfolio



